# Full-Stack Flask Application

A full-stack web application with Flask backend and browser-based frontend.

## Features

- **Backend**: Flask server with RESTful API endpoints
- **Frontend**: Modern HTML/CSS/JavaScript interface
- **Backend Logic**: All processing happens on the Python backend
- **Local Development**: Runs entirely on your local machine

## Project Structure

```
laddu/
├── app.py                 # Flask backend application
├── requirements.txt       # Python dependencies
├── templates/
│   └── index.html        # Frontend HTML
└── static/
    ├── style.css         # Frontend styles
    └── script.js         # Frontend JavaScript
```

## Setup Instructions

### 1. Install Python Dependencies

```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

### 2. Run the Flask Server

```bash
python app.py
```

The server will start on `http://localhost:5000`

### 3. Open in Browser

Once the server is running, open your browser and navigate to:
```
http://localhost:5000
```

## API Endpoints

- `GET /` - Serves the main HTML page
- `GET /api/data` - Get all stored data
- `POST /api/data` - Add new data (requires JSON body with `message` field)
- `DELETE /api/data/<id>` - Delete data by ID
- `POST /api/process` - Process text on the backend (requires JSON body with `text` field)

## How It Works

1. **Backend (Flask)**: Handles all business logic, data processing, and API requests
2. **Frontend (Browser)**: Sends requests to the backend API and displays results
3. **Communication**: Frontend uses JavaScript `fetch()` to communicate with Flask API endpoints

## Example Usage

1. **Add Data**: Enter a message in the "Add Data" section and submit
2. **Process Text**: Enter text in the "Process Text" section to see backend processing (word count, character count, reversed text, etc.)
3. **View Data**: All stored data appears in the "Stored Data" section
4. **Delete Data**: Click the delete button on any item to remove it

## Notes

- The backend runs on port 5000 by default
- All data is stored in memory (will be lost on server restart)
- For production, consider using a database instead of in-memory storage
- CORS is enabled to allow frontend-backend communication

